4 The old geographers represented Europe as a rough triangle,

· of which the apex was formed by the bend of the Tanais (Don), and the other two angles by the Columns of Hercules and the British Isles. Dante's immediate authority was probably Albertus Magnus, who in his De Natura Locorum (iii. 7) says: ‘Europa . . . habet figuram trigoni circumfusam mari oceano, quantum ad nostram habitabilem. Trigonus autem ex arcubus et non lineis rectis componitur, licet acies angulorum non cadant omnino in acumen' (see my article Some Unacknowledyed Obliyations of Dante to Albertus Magnus, in Romania, xxiv. 411-123 and Moore, studies in Dante, iii. 125-6).
